Privacy Policy

Last modified: November 12, 2019

 

Introduction

Accreditation Council for Graduate Medical Education (“ACGME,” "Company," or "We") respects your privacy and is committed to protecting it through our compliance with this policy.

This policy describes the types of information we may collect from you or that you may provide when you download the ACGME Direct Observation of Clinical Performance (DOCP) app (our "App") and our practices for collecting, using, maintaining, protecting, and disclosing that information. This Privacy Policy only pertains to information collected by ACGME through the App.

We detect and use the IP address of users downloading the App in order to assist us with diagnosing and solving problems with the server and to assist with the administration of the App. Other than that, the ACGME nor 5-Nines, the app host, does not collect any personal data.

Notwithstanding anything to the contrary herein, we will not share any limited personal information gathered on this site with third parties except in limited circumstances as identified below.

If you do not agree to be bound by the terms and conditions of this Privacy Policy, please do not access and download the App.

 

Changes to the App Privacy Policy

As the ACGME DOCP app may change from time to time, this Privacy Policy is expected to change as well. ACGME reserves the right to change this policy at any time for any reason. We will post a notice that this Privacy Policy has been amended by revising the “Last modified” date at the top of this page.

 

Web Cookies and Other Forms of User Recognition

Google Play and the Apple Store collect information about use of this App.  The tools they use collect information such as how many users download the App, on what date and time, from what page they were directed to the app, the users’ IP addresses, and what other sites they used prior to coming to this App. Google Play and the Apple Store are able to identify you as a unique user the next time you visit this App, however this information is not available to anyone except Google or Apple. Google’s and Apple’s ability to use and share information they collect about your visits to this site is restricted by the Google Play’s and Apple Store’s Terms of Use and their respective Privacy Policies.

We use the limited information we get from the Google Play and the Apple Store only to improve this App. Google Play and the Apple Store share only your Device type and version, and your Country, Language and Carrier on the date you download the App; they do not ever share your name or other identifying information. The data is collected directly by Google Play or the Apple Store; neither the ACGME nor 5-Nines, the app host, combines the information collected through the use of Google or Apple tools with any personally identifiable information. This information is collected for statistical purposes and to make the App more useful to visitors. ACGME does not collect personal information about individual users nor do we supply personal or financial information about individual users to third parties. The ACGME and 5-Nines do use cookies to maintain App information to assist in App navigation. The server hosting the DOCP Word Press app detects only a visitor’s access information including download date and time, their IP address, and the pages they visited. Use of this data is limited to diagnosing and solving problems with the server and to assist with the administration of the App.

 

Personal Information

In the course of app operation, the limited information collected by the App may be stored and processed in the United States. ACGME may collect, hold, and use, directly or through its affiliates, contractors, successors, assigns, and agents, the personally identifiable information you submit through the site.

The ACGME cooperates with law enforcement inquiries and enforcement activities. ACGME may monitor, edit, or disclose your personal information, if required to do so in order to comply with any valid legal process or governmental request (such as a search warrant, subpoena, statute, or court order). Any and all data collected by or on behalf of ACGME relating any use of the App or its content by any users is and shall remain at all times the sole property of ACGME.

We may use the information collected in a de-identified format for research, quality improvement, or benchmarking purposes, and may provide this information in the aggregate to third parties. For example, we might inform other users about the number of users that have downloaded the App.

We may contract with other companies or individuals to help us provide services, such as development or maintenance of the App. We require others to comply with the Privacy Policy and limit their access to only the information that is necessary to accomplish the task at hand and nothing more. Unless otherwise specified above, your personal information will not be provided to any third parties.

 

Security Policy

We treat data as an asset that must be protected against loss and unauthorized access. This server hosting this Word Press app has security policies and technology in place to protect the loss, misuse, and alteration of the limited information (e.g. visitor IP address) under ACGME control. No personal information beyond a visitor’s IP address is collected and procedural and technical safeguards are used to protect all information  under its control against loss or theft as well as unauthorized access and disclosure. We cannot, however, protect against user misuse, loss, or alteration of a user's own information. Although ACGME makes every reasonable attempt to ensure your  information is secure, there is always some risk in transmitting information across the Internet. We cannot guarantee that the personal information we collect will never be disclosed in some manner not consistent with this Privacy Policy. We also cannot protect against User misuse, loss, or alteration of any user editable content.

 

Contact

To ask questions or comment about this Privacy Policy and our privacy practices, e-mail de@acgme.org.

Using the Direct Observation of Clinical Care App

 

Medical educators have a major responsibility to evaluate the clinical skills of learners and to provide learners with timely, useful feedback to ensure continued professional development toward expertise and correction of deficiencies. The core clinical skills of interviewing, physical examination, clinical reasoning, breaking bad news, handoffs, and counseling remain essential to the successful care of patients.

Direct observation is an essential method for the effective and valid assessment of these critical clinical skills, as it focuses on the actual abilities of learners’ interactions and care of patients. Effective assessment through direct observation helps to ensure patients receive high-quality care, help faculty members provide specific and timely feedback and coaching, and ensure faculty members make proper supervision decisions. The following equation helps to reinforce the importance of direct observation:

Learner ability X appropriate level of faculty supervision must = safe, effective, patient-centered care.

“X” represents the critical interaction between learner and faculty members to achieve the desired outcome for the patient.

Learner abilities in these clinical skills exist on a developmental continuum. Direct observation can provide important data on Milestone stages in the competencies of patient care, medical knowledge, and interpersonal skills and communication.

This direct observation of clinical care (DOCC) assessment tool provides evidence-based frameworks designed to be a guide before and during observations. The frameworks should not be used as a rigid checklist, as faculty member judgment remains important. They should be used as a cognitive support to ensure faculty members are looking for key behaviors known to affect patient outcomes. It is recommended these frameworks are shared often and freely with learners, as they can be used to support a feedback conversation after the observation.

Finally, the DOCC also provides user instructions and a tip sheet to help faculty improve their direct observation.

The direct observation of clinical care exists to help all learners, faculty members, and programs increase the frequency of observation, improve the quality of feedback and coaching, and most importantly, the quality of patient care.

item.title: Tips for Direct Observation
item.dc:creator: kcgh5
item.content:encoded:
[et_pb_section fb_built="1" admin_label="section" _builder_version="4.4.9"][et_pb_row column_structure="1_2,1_2" _builder_version="4.2.2" custom_margin="||5px||false|false" custom_padding="||5px||false|false"][et_pb_column type="1_2" _builder_version="4.2.2"][et_pb_text _builder_version="4.3.2" header_text_color="#00718f" hover_enabled="0" sticky_enabled="0"]

TIPS FOR INCREASING DIRECT OBSERVATION

[/et_pb_text][et_pb_accordion open_toggle_text_color="#00718f" closed_toggle_background_color="#e2e9ec" icon_color="#00718f" _builder_version="4.6.0" toggle_text_color="#00718f" hover_enabled="0" border_width_all="0px" sticky_enabled="0"][et_pb_accordion_item title="Sampling" open="on" _builder_version="4.6.0" hover_enabled="0" sticky_enabled="0"]
  • It is acceptable to watch part of an encounter (i.e., history OR physical exam OR counseling).
  • It is also acceptable to watch part of a part of an encounter such as part of the history (i.e., agenda setting); part of the physical exam (e.g., cardiovascular or shoulder exam), as long as the goal of the observation is clear.
[/et_pb_accordion_item][et_pb_accordion_item title="Outpatient Setting" _builder_version="4.6.0" hover_enabled="0" open="off" sticky_enabled="0"]

HISTORY TAKING

  • Watch the first five minutes of an encounter to observe agenda-setting skills.
  • During each clinic, observe the first resident/patient encounter of the session (usually no resident/fellow is ready to present in the first 10 minutes of clinic).
  • Ask the resident who the most challenging patient is on the schedule and watch that encounter. Residents/fellows often find feedback on “challenging patients” very helpful. Examples include patients who are tangential (watch how redirection is done), ask for pain medications, or are poorly adherent.
  • Consider focusing the observation on specific topic areas such as assessment of the geriatric patient, medication reconciliation, or assessment of health literacy.

PHYSICAL EXAM

  • Tell the resident/fellow to take a history but find the faculty member before doing the physical exam. This works particularly well for the pelvic exam and joint exams (i.e., back, hip, knee, shoulder); patients appreciate it when a painful joint gets manipulated only once.

COUNSELING

  • Tell the resident/fellow not to review the plan of care with the patient. Watch counseling (e.g., discussion of tests to be ordered).
  • Watch the resident/fellow start a patient on a new medication and observe that conversation.
  • Watch the resident/fellow counsel a patient on behavioral change (e.g., weight loss counseling, smoking cessation counseling).
  • Watch the resident/fellow counsel a patient on immunizations (e.g., flu shot) or on screening (e.g. prostate cancer screenings, mammogram for patients 40-50 years old).

 

[/et_pb_accordion_item][et_pb_accordion_item title="Inpatient Setting" _builder_version="4.6.0" hover_enabled="0" open="off" sticky_enabled="0"]

HISTORY TAKING

  • Watch part of an admission history. As attending, the faculty member will need to see the patient anyway so make this a “twofer.”
  • Watch pre-rounding. This saves time because the history, exam, and counseling are covered and the patient doesn’t have to be seen later in the day. Come in early to pre-round or tell the learner to save one patient for attending rounds.
  • Ask the learner to retake the history in a night float or hand-off patient.

PHYSICAL EXAM

  • Watch the physical exam during pre-rounding. This saves time because the history, exam, and counseling are covered and the patient doesn’t have to be seen later in the day. Come in early to pre-round or tell the learner to save one patient for attending rounds.
  • Take the team to the bedside and ask a team member unfamiliar with the patient to lead the exam (i.e., a cardiovascular exam and assessment of volume status in a patient admitted with heart failure; a neurologic exam in a patient admitted with stroke or change in mental status).
  • Have a team member lead the physical exam on a night float or hand-off patient.

COUNSELING

  • Watch counseling during pre-rounding.
  • After rounds, when a patient needs to be updated on the care plan (i.e., it changed on rounds), watch the resident/fellow review it with the patient.
  • Observe the resident/fellow obtain informed consent for a procedure.
  • Observe the resident/fellow breaking bad news.
  • Observe the resident/fellow holding a family meeting.
  • Observe the resident/fellow reviewing a test result with a patient.
  • Observe the resident/fellow reviewing the discharge plan with the patient.
  • Observe a code status discussion.

 

[/et_pb_accordion_item][et_pb_accordion_item title="Two (or Even Three) Birds with One Stone" _builder_version="4.6.0" hover_enabled="0" open="off" sticky_enabled="0"]

IDENTIFY SITUATIONS WHERE OBSERVATION CAN HELP THE LEARNER AND THE PATIENT

  • Observing history taking works well for a learner who always runs late in clinic and gives an opportunity to identify what takes the learner so long.
  • Ask learners what they have not done before (e.g., a geriatric assessment, the musculoskeletal exam, starting insulin in a patient with poorly controlled diabetes, advanced directives, family meeting). That situation is perfect for observation.

 

[/et_pb_accordion_item][et_pb_accordion_item title="Create a Simple System for Tracking" _builder_version="4.6.0" hover_enabled="0" open="off" sticky_enabled="0"]

Make a document with three columns (see example below). The first column lists all the residents/fellows in clinic or on service, the second lists the target number of observations, and the third is a place to mark when an observation is completed. Staple the document to a folder that contains the mini-CEX (or other direct observation tool). Hang the folder in the clinic precepting room or conference room. Tally observations throughout the day. Start each clinic/day by looking to see who needs to be observed.

 

Resident/Fellows in Clinic/Service Target # of Observations Observation is Complete
• • •
• • •
• • •
[/et_pb_accordion_item][et_pb_accordion_item title="Other Tips for Direct Observation" _builder_version="4.6.0" hover_enabled="0" open="off" sticky_enabled="0"]
  • Make observations based on the competencies and goals of the residency or fellowship program.
  • Use the Milestones as a guide when choosing what to observe
  • Try to embed the observation in the work already being done.
  • Observe each learner multiple times to improve the generalizability of the assessments.
  • Build meaningful feedback into the direct observation process and make sure feedback includes an action plan: what steps can the learner take to improve in a particular area?

 

[/et_pb_accordion_item][/et_pb_accordion][/et_pb_column][et_pb_column type="1_2" _builder_version="4.6.0" _module_preset="default"][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][/et_pb_section]

item.title: Framework: History Taking
item.dc:creator: kcgh5
item.content:encoded:
History Taking Framework

Sets the Stage

  • Knocks on door before entering or asks permission to enter patient’s space
  • Greets patient appropriately
  • Thanks patient for waiting; apologizes if late
  • Ensures patient readiness and privacy
  • Determines how a new patient would like to be addressed and calls patient by preferred name (new patient)
  • Introduces self to a new patient
  • Starts both the first and return visits with social talk/small talk
  • Removes barriers to communication (e.g., sits down before starting interview, makes eye contact, uses open body language)
  • Makes patient comfortable

Elicits Chief Concerns/Sets the Agenda

  • Indicates time available (e.g., “in this visit” or “in the time we have today”)
  • Obtains list of all issues patient wants to discuss; asks patient to prioritize list
  • Indicates physician’s needs
  • Summarizes agenda and negotiates

Begins with Non-Focusing Questions to Help Patient Express Self

  • Starts with open-ended question (unless inappropriate)
  • Uses non-focusing open-ended skills (uses open ended questions, uses silence, makes neutral utterances, doesn’t interrupt)
  • Obtains information from nonverbal sources

Uses Focusing Skills to Elicit Symptom Story, Personal and Emotional Content

  • Obtains description of symptom(s) (i.e., elicits physical symptom story in open ended way, reflecting, echoing, requesting ("tell me more"), summarizing)
  • Explores personal context (i.e., broader personal/psychological context of symptoms, beliefs, attributions, and cultural, conceptual, social, and spiritual considerations)
  • Elicits emotional context directly (i.e., "how did that make you feel?") or indirectly (i.e., illness' impact on life); elicits beliefs about the problem, patient triggers for seeking care)
  • Responds to patient’s feelings/emotions using NURS (Naming, Understanding/legitimizing, Respecting, Supporting) to express empathy
  • Expands the story by continuing to elicit personal and emotional context addressing feelings and emotions

Transitions to Middle of Interview

  • Summarizes history briefly
  • Checks history accuracy (asks patient, "Is that correct?")
  • Indicates content and style of inquiry will change when patient is ready; announces shift to doctor-centered questions

Obtains Remainder of History

  • Obtains pertinent history via hypothesis testing to make accurate diagnosis/differential diagnosis
  • Sequences questions logically to demonstrate clinical reasoning
  • Avoids directive leading questions (“You are not having any abdominal pain.”)
  • Asks questions one at a time allowing adequate time for patient to respond
  • Asks relevant past medical history as pertains to chief complaint
  • Makes normalizing statements before questions
  • Asks relevant family history as pertains to chief complaint
  • Asks relevant review of systems as pertains to chief complaint

Wraps Up the History

  • Ensures understanding of actual reason for patient’s visit using patient’s initial characterization of the problem
  • Addresses and answers all patient questions

Uses of Electronic Health Record (EHR) Appropriately

  • Greets the patient before turning to computer screen
  • Introduces EHR, how it will be used, and asks for permission to type
  • Acknowledges they have reviewed the EHR or that the conversation aligns with/complements the information in the EHR
  • Positions screen as a bridge, not a divider
  • Invites patient’s concerns rather than using them as a screen prompt
  • Shares screen with patient (e.g., invites patient to look at screen; reads what is being written)
  • Appropriately divides encounter into patient- and computer-focused stages
  • Explains prolonged typing or reading pauses (at least once)
  • Moves head, eyes, and body toward patient and removes hands from keyboard/mouse to give patient undivided attention when needed

References

Duke, Pamela, Richard M. Frankel, and Shmuel Reis. 2013. “How to Integrate the Electronic Health Record and Patient-Centered Communication into the Medical Visit: A Skills-Based Approach.” Teaching and Learning in Medicine 25 (4): 358-65. doi:10.1080/10401334.2013.827981. Frankel, Richard, Terry Stein. 1999. “Getting the Most out of the Clinical Encounter: The Four Habits Model.” The Permanente Journal 3 (3): 79-88. doi:10.7812/tpp/99-020. Lane, J. Lindsey, Ruth P. Gottlieb. 2000. “Structured Clinical Observations: A Method to Teach Clinical Skills with Limited Time and Financial Resources.” Pediatrics 105(4): 973-977. Lyles, J.S., F.C. Dwamena, C. Lein, and R.C. Smith. 2001. “Evidence-Based Patient-Centered Interviewing.” Journal of Clinical Outcome Management 8 (7): 28-33.

item.title: Framework: Counseling/Shared Decision Making
item.dc:creator: kcgh5
item.content:encoded:
Counseling/Shared Decision-Making Framework

Setting the Stage and Getting Started

  • Begins by orienting patient to the end of interview (e.g., "will be discussing assessment and plan")
  • Asks if patient would like someone else present
  • Assesses what patient knows (i.e., patient understanding) before telling

Discussing the Clinical Issue/Diagnosis/Nature of Decision

  • Explains diagnosis/prognosis incorporating patient’s informational needs; connects language of symptom description to diagnosis
  • Assesses patient readiness to address the topic, and/or invoke change

Shared Decision Making

  • Discusses patient role in decision making (e.g., have an explicit discussion that there is a decision to make)
  • Discusses clinical issue or nature of the decision
  • Discusses alternatives
  • Discusses pros and cons of alternatives
  • Discusses uncertainties with the decision made (complex decision only)
  • Assesses patient understanding
  • Explores patient preference/willingness to follow recommendation

Content of Plan

  • Provides medically accurate and complete plan
  • Identifies SMART  (Specific, Measurable, Attainable, Relevant, Time-bound) goal acceptable to patient
  • Discusses medication name, number pills per day, how to take the medication, and side effects
  • Presents plan in an organized manner

Wrapping Up

  • Addresses patient’s barriers to recommendation (e.g., financial, social, cultural)
  • Summarizes decisions; provides written plans/instructions appropriate to patient’s level of health literacy
  • Discusses patient’s ability and confidence to follow agreed-upon plan
  • Uses teach-back method, so patient explains the diagnosis and instructions in own words
  • Arranges follow-up
  • Indicates reasons for sooner follow-up
  • Supports patient before saying goodbye

Behaviors Throughout Encounter

  • Demonstrates appropriate, open body language; sits down
  • Uses appropriate facial expression, tone of voice
  • Makes good eye contact
  • Speaks plainly/avoids jargon; adapts conversation to patient’s level of understanding
  • Gives information in small chunks with frequent pauses; conversation is a back-and-forth, not a data dump; uses silence appropriately.
  • Encourages patient to ask questions throughout discussion
  • Addresses and answers patient’s questions and validates and/or acknowledges patient’s concerns
  • Elicits/addresses patient’s emotional verbal and non-verbal reactions; reflects what patient is saying, shows empathy, concern and makes empathic comments

Use of Electronic Health Record

  • Appropriately divides encounter into patient- and computer-focused stages
  • Shares screen with patient (i.e., invites patient to look at what's being written; reads what's being written; reviews data with patient)
  • Moves head, eyes, body to patient and removes hands from keyboard/mouse to give patient undivided attention when needed
  • Uses computer for patient education support (e.g., online risk calculators, handouts) (or provides other educational materials)

References

Hasenberg, Tracy L. Laidley, and Wendy Levinson. 1999. “Informed Decision Making in Outpatient Practice.” JAMA. 282 (24): 2313. doi:10.1001/jama.282.24.2313. Duke, Pamela, Richard M. item.title: Framework: Clinical Reasoning
item.dc:creator: kcgh5
item.content:encoded:
Clinical Reasoning Framework

Did the learner collect/report history and examination data in a hypothesis-directed manner?
MINIMAL • Non-directed in questioning and exam • Asked questions without clear focus on potential diagnoses PARTIAL • Questioning and exam generally reflective of potential diagnoses, but some less relevant or tangential questions COMPLETE • Followed clear line of inquiry, directing questioning and exam to specific findings likely to increase or decrease likelihood of specific diagnoses
Did the learner articulate a complete problem representation using descriptive medical terminology?
MINIMAL • Included extraneous information • Missed key findings • Did not translate findings into medical terminology PARTIAL • Generally included key clinical findings (both positive and negative) but either missed some key findings or missed important descriptive medical terminology COMPLETE • Gave clear synopsis of clinical problem • Emphasized important positive and negative findings using descriptive medical terminology
Did the learner articulate a prioritized differential diagnosis of most likely, less likely, unlikely, and "can't miss" diagnoses based on the problem representation?
MINIMAL • Missed key elements of differential diagnosis, including likely diagnoses or "can't miss" diagnoses PARTIAL • Gave differential diagnosis that included likely and "can't miss" diagnoses but either missed key diagnoses or ranked them inappropriately COMPLETE • Gave accurately ranked differential diagnosis including likely and "can't miss" diagnoses
Did the learner direct evaluation/treatment towards high priority diagnoses?
MINIMAL • Directed evaluation and treatment toward unlikely/unimportant diagnoses • Did not evaluate or treat for most likely/"can't miss" diagnoses PARTIAL • Major focus of evaluation and treatment was likely and "can't miss" diagnoses but included non-essential testing COMPLETE • Efficiently directed evaluation and treatment towards most likely and "can't miss" diagnoses • Deferred tests directed towards less likely or less important diagnoses

Did the learner demonstrate the ability to think about their own thinking (metacognition)?

Consider asking: Is there anything about the way you are thinking or feeling about this case that may lead to error? MINIMAL • Not able to describe the influence of cognitive tendencies or emotional/situational factors that may have influenced decision making PARTIAL/COMPLETE • Can name one cognitive tendency or emotional/situational factor that may have influenced decision making

item.title: Framework: Breaking Bad News
item.dc:creator: kcgh5
item.content:encoded:
[et_pb_section fb_built="1" _builder_version="3.22"][et_pb_row _builder_version="3.25" background_size="initial" background_position="top_left" background_repeat="repeat"][et_pb_column type="4_4" _builder_version="3.25" custom_padding="|||" custom_padding__hover="|||"][et_pb_text _builder_version="4.6.0" background_size="initial" background_position="top_left" background_repeat="repeat"]

Framework: Breaking Bad News

 

S: Setting up the interview

  • Arranges for private, quiet setting
  • Has tissues ready
  • Involves significant others if desired by patient
  • Sits down
  • Removes physical barriers and sits close to patient
  • Makes connection with patient (e.g., eye contact, appropriate touch)
  • Manages time constraints/interruptions (e.g., turns off pager/phone/tells staff)
  • Arranges for a trained health care interpreter if language difficulties are present
  • Is sensitive to the patient’s cultural, racial, religious and social background

 

P: Assess the patient’s perception (i.e. before telling, asks)

  • Uses open-ended questions to learn how patient perceives situation (i.e., "What have you been told about your situation so far?"; or "What is your understanding of why we did [x] test?")
  • Corrects misinformation
  • Tailors information to what patient understands

 

I: Invitation: Obtain patient’s invitation (ideally at time of test ordering)

  • Identifies how patient would like to get information; all information, or general information and more time on plan; how much about prognosis

 

K: Knowledge: Giving knowledge and information

  • Gives warning shot (i.e., "I am sorry to tell you" or "Unfortunately I have some bad news.")
  • Gives accurate medical facts
  • Adjusts conversation to comprehension/vocabulary of patient; provides information simply and honestly with careful, direct word choice, using no euphemisms.
  • Avoids technical diagnostic terminology, avoids medical jargon
  • Avoids excessive bluntness
  • Gives information in small chunks and periodically checking patient understanding
  • Maintains hope and avoids the message that “nothing can be done” (i.e., always palliative)

 

E: Address emotions with empathic responses

  • Identifies emotions experienced by patient (i.e., asks the patient what the patient is thinking or feeling)
  • Allows patient time to express feelings
  • Handles the patient’s emotional reactions
  • Demonstrates warmth, caring, and empathy

 

S: Strategy and summary

  • Asks patient if ready to discuss treatment plan or next steps
  • Arranges a time to review the situation
  • Discusses treatment options
  • Offers assistance in breaking the news to others
  • Provides information about support services
  • Documents the information given and summarizes the discussion verbally and in written format
  • Solicits questions

 

References:

Baile WF, Buckman R, Lenzi R et al. SPIKES—A Six-Step Protocol for Delivering Bad News: Application to the Patient with Cancer. The Oncologist 2000;5:302-11.

Ptacek JT, Eberhardt TL. Breaking bad news:a review of the literature. JAMA. 1996;276:496-502.

[/et_pb_text][/et_pb_column][/et_pb_row][/et_pb_section]

item.title: Framework: Hand-off
item.dc:creator: kcgh5
item.content:encoded:
Hand-off Framework

I-PASS

I: Illness severity

  • Indicates if patient is potentially unstable, or unstable

P: Patient summary

  • Gives summary statement to next clinician to provide care
  • Describes events leading up to admission
  • Describes hospital course
  • Includes ongoing assessment
  • Includes plan

A: Action list

  • Gives to-do list
  • Includes timeline and ownership

S: Situation awareness and contingency planning

  • Know what’s going on
  • Plan for what might happen

S: Synthesis by receiver

  • Receiver (i.e., next clinician to provide care) summarizes what was heard
  • Receiver asks questions
  • Receiver restates key action/to do items
Starmer, A. J. et al. 2012. "I-PASS." Pediatrics 129 (2):201-204.

SIGN-OUT

S: Sick or Do Not Resusitate (DNR)

  • Highlights sick or unstable patients, identifies patients wit DNR/Do Not Intubate (DNI) directives

I: Identifying data

  • Provides name, age, gender, and diagnosis

G: General hospital course

  • Includes general hospital course

N: New events of the day

  • Includes new events of the day

O: Overall health status/clinical condition

  • Gives overall status/condition of patient now

U: Upcoming possibilities

  • Provides upcoming possibilities
  • Provides potential plan and rationale

T: Tasks

  • Provides tasks to complete overnight with plan
  • Provides rationale for tasks
  • Asks if any questions

Resources:

L.I. Horwitz. T. Moin, M.L. Green. 2007. “Development and Implementation of an Oral Sign-Out Skills Curriculum.” Journal of General Internal Medicine 22 (10): 1470-1474.

item.title: Summary Statement
item.dc:creator: kcgh5
item.content:encoded:
Summary Statement

The purpose of a summary statement is to help you synthesize your specific observations into prioritized key themes to share with the resident/fellow. For example, if a resident doesn’t introduce him/herself to the patient, ask the patient’s name, or make small talk, these are all fall into the theme of setting the stage to interact with the patient and establishing rapport with them. Think of a summary statement as a kind of topic sentence. The multiple observations you have made become the specific points that support the summary statement. An example summary statement might be: The resident did an excellent job establishing rapport with the patient and setting the agenda, but needs to improve her skills in hypothesis-driven history taking.
